&gt;  I thought after I wrote the comment about being more fluent in reading QS
&gt; that it might be disconcerting.  I read two of the articles in the News in
&gt; QS with interest today, and I have been reading what others are writing by
&gt; hand in QS without problems in recent weeks.  I write it fluently just as
&gt; Moira mentioned she does.  The problem is not with QS but with the amount of
&gt; practice that we receive.  I just cannot read QS as fast as TO, which is not
&gt; surprising when you consider that we are surrounded by TO all the time and
&gt; that we learned it as children. I daresay that if as a child you had been
&gt; told how TO worked, but were given no reading practice in it, no one around
&gt; you used it, and you never received anything written in it, you would be
&gt; just as slow at reading TO as you are now at reading QS.
&gt;
&gt;  I would like to attain the reading speed in QS that I have in TO.  That
&gt; goal is still some distance away, but it is getting closer.  For the first
&gt; time, with the ability to communicate effectively in QS and to read
&gt; articles, news, etc. written in it, I have no question that goal can be
&gt; attained.  I can already see that my QS reading speed has been increasing in
&gt; recent weeks.  And even now, I&#39;m not reading QS every day.
&gt;
&gt;  Just as a beginning TO reader sounds words out, we have to do that in QS
&gt; until we begin to automatically recognize word outlines.  Until recently
&gt; that has not been feasible because there are too few of us, and we tend to
&gt; only read what we write ourselves.  For instance, I take notes in QS as
&gt; secretary of a club I&#39;m in.  I then go back and transliterate them on the
&gt; computer for the club records.  Thus, my reading speed isn&#39;t critical and QS
&gt; is still useful.
&gt;
&gt;  A fluent reader recognizes words at sight and doesn&#39;t have to break them
&gt; down into individual syllables or letters.  However, in reading your news
&gt; today, I saw numerous words in QS for the first time.  The shorter, common
&gt; words I read quickly and essentially automatically just as I do in TO.  But
&gt; three, four and five syllable words that are unfamiliar are a different
&gt; matter.  Here are a few words I remember reading in QS for the first time
&gt; today, and there are countless others: Islamabad, Islamic militants,
&gt; Afghanistan, Land Cruiser, bullet-proofed (this last one hasn&#39;t come up much
&gt; in my personal note-taking.)   :-).
&gt;
&gt;  Since the term &quot;Islamic militants&quot; was in the Pakistan story several times,
&gt; it began looking familiar by the end of the story, but that is what has to
&gt; occur to build up reading speed.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;  Paige
&gt;
&gt;  P.S.  Here is an example of the pressure we face against using QS.  A few
&gt; years ago, I was taking notes in QS in a case.  Later my father, with whom I
&gt; practiced, would be looking at a file, and tell me that I needed to write in
&gt; TO.  His customary comment was, &quot;What if you get hit by a bus, and I have to
&gt; take this case over.  I won&#39;t be able to read your notes.&quot;  The same problem
&gt; exists when my secretary is working on a document and has to refer to the
&gt; file.  If there are notes in QS, I have to rewrite them for her, which isn&#39;t
&gt; exactly a time-saver.
&gt;
&gt;  What would be interesting would be for someone to teach their child to read
&gt; QS before they go to school and see how easily they take to it.
